faqs:
  - q: "What's the difference between a marginal and effective tax rate?"
    a: "The marginal rate is the rate applied to your last dollar of income — the bracket your top dollar falls into. The effective rate is your total tax divided by total taxable income. Effective is always lower than marginal because the lower brackets get taxed at their lower rates first."
  - q: "Does crossing into a higher bracket tax all my income at the higher rate?"
    a: "No. Only the dollars above the bracket threshold are taxed at the higher rate. The income below stays taxed at the lower rates. This is why a raise that crosses a bracket never reduces your take-home pay overall."
  - q: "Does this calculator include state tax?"
    a: "No. It estimates federal income tax only. State tax varies widely (some states have none, others use brackets or flat rates), so add your state's effective rate separately when planning your full tax bill."
  - q: "What income should I enter — gross or taxable?"
    a: "Enter taxable income, which is roughly gross income minus the standard deduction or itemized deductions, and any above-the-line adjustments. If you're not sure of your taxable income, use your gross income as a directional approximation — the tool will still give you a useful planning figure."
  - q: "Are these brackets the official 2026 IRS brackets?"
    a: "The calculator uses the 2026 federal bracket structure for planning. Always cross-check the IRS's published tables for your filing year before relying on the figure for actual tax preparation."
